          "body": "Verses 15-21 shift from reflective wisdom to raw lament. The pivot at verse 15 is maintained by a single phrase: 'my eyes are continually toward the Lord' (tamid, always). David's continuous gaze toward God is not a technique — it is the only thing keeping him from despair as he describes his condition: lonely (yachid — 'only one,' isolated), afflicted (ani — pressed down), heart-troubles enlarged (25:17), distressed, surrounded by enemies 'many' and hating with 'violent hatred' (chamas, the word used of pre-flood wickedness in Genesis 6:11). The lament does not resolve the pain by explaining it. It brings it before God as it is. Spurgeon noted that 'the very reason David pleads for grace is his misery; his loneliness and affliction are arguments which he urges with God' (*The Treasury of David*, vol. 1). The closing verse of the personal section (25:21) is a statement of confidence: 'Let integrity and uprightness preserve me, for I wait for You.' The waiting (qavah) that opened the psalm (25:3, 5) closes it — the entire arc from petition to lament ends in the same posture of covenantal waiting."
